### (a) Overall naturalness: 5/10

Individually, several definitions sound plausibly dictionary-like. As a set, however, they feel generated from a rigid imitation of dictionary prose. Nearly every entry follows the same architecture: a concise core gloss, a semicolon, and then an elaboration, contrast, secondary sense, or taxonomic qualification.

The strongest entries are professionally plausible—for example:

> “capable of being seen; perceptible by the eye, whether directly or with the aid of an instrument”

But the longer entries become over-engineered and encyclopedic:

> “it may be hollow or solid, and its size and weight are fixed by the game in which it is used, ranging from the small hard sphere of golf to the large inflated sphere of football”

A real editorial team might produce some sentences like these, especially in an older dictionary. It would be unlikely to produce twelve consecutive entries with virtually the same punctuation and clause-building strategy.

### (b) Structural tells

The clearest tell is the universal semicolon hinge. All twelve definitions contain exactly one semicolon dividing the main gloss from appended material:

> “a male parent; a man considered in relation to his child or children…”

> “to form by putting parts or materials together; to bring into existence…”

> “capable of being seen; perceptible by the eye…”

> “contrary to morality or to accepted standards; deserving of blame or censure”

Semicolons are normal in dictionaries, but this level of invariance is not. A real collection would mix commas, separate numbered senses, parenthetical labels, colons, multiple semicolons, and very short unexpanded definitions.

A second pattern is **core definition + mechanically appended clarification**. The first clause identifies the category; everything after the semicolon is a standardized add-on:

- Factual expansion:  
  > “the breeds differ widely in size and form”

- Usage or storage note:  
  > “commonly one of a list maintained within a web browser”

- Secondary or extended sense:  
  > “also, any close encircling hold or pressure”

- Contrast with neighboring concepts:  
  > “it differs from mere rest in the loss of awareness, and from a swoon or coma…”

- Moral consequence:  
  > “deserving of blame or censure”

These tail clauses repeatedly sound as though the system has finished defining the word but is required to add one more fact.

A third tell is **overuse of balanced binary or ternary constructions**:

> “hollow or solid”

> “size and weight”

> “companion or working animal”

> “affection, comfort, or greeting”

> “parts or materials”

> “directly or with the aid of an instrument”

> “blame or censure”

Again, such coordination is normal by itself. Its density across the set gives the prose a manufactured rhythm.

There is also repeated **taxonomic contrast by parallel prepositional phrases**:

> “whether they are begotten by him or adopted”

> “from mere rest in the loss of awareness, and from a swoon or coma in the ease with which it is broken”

> “distinguished from a girl by full growth and maturity, and from a man by the capacity to bear children”

That last example is especially conspicuous: “from X by Y, and from Z by W” is logically tidy but mechanically symmetrical.

The openings are formulaic too. Most use one of only a few frames:

- **Indefinite noun phrase:** “a rounded object…,” “a stored record…,” “a domesticated… mammal…,” “a male parent…,” “an embrace…”
- **Infinitive:** “to enter…,” “to form…”
- **Participial/adjectival category label:** “(of a person…),” “capable of…,” “(of an act…)”

Those are legitimate dictionary constructions, but the entries rarely depart from them through sense numbering, usage labels, elliptical definitions, cross-references, or genuinely different syntactic formats.

Finally, several longer entries accumulate clauses in an unnaturally regular staircase:

> “a rounded object employed in games and sports, typically struck, kicked, or thrown; it may be hollow or solid, and its size and weight are fixed by the game in which it is used, ranging…”

That is category → typical actions → physical alternatives → regulation → examples. It reads like information slotted into a schema.

### (c) Worst and best

The least natural is entry 1:

> “a rounded object employed in games and sports, typically struck, kicked, or thrown; it may be hollow or solid, and its size and weight are fixed by the game in which it is used, ranging from the small hard sphere of golf to the large inflated sphere of football”

It is overloaded, and “the sphere of golf” and “the sphere of football” are unnatural substitutions for “golf ball” and “football.” Structurally, it keeps appending attributes after the word is already adequately defined.

Entry 6 is also strongly templated:

> “a male parent; a man considered in relation to his child or children, whether they are begotten by him or adopted; correspondingly, a male animal considered in relation to its own offspring”

It is the only entry with two semicolons, but that extra division merely reveals the machinery more clearly: basic gloss → human version → biological qualification → corresponding animal version. “Correspondingly” sounds like a generated transition rather than tight lexicographic editing.

Entry 11 is another weak one:

> “an adult female human being; distinguished from a girl by full growth and maturity, and from a man by the capacity to bear children”

The perfectly balanced “from a girl by…, and from a man by…” construction feels schematic. Apart from its questionable definitional content, its sentence structure tries too visibly to fill both sides of a classification grid.

Entry 8 is awkward in a more local way:

> “to bring into existence, as a craftsman does a chair or a cook a meal”

The ellipsis in “does a chair” and “does … a meal” is not natural English for the intended meaning. A professional editor would likely write “as a craftsman makes a chair or a cook prepares a meal”—though that becomes circular if the headword is *make*.

The most natural are entries 4, 10, and 12:

> “(of a person, animal, or plant) no longer alive; having permanently ceased the functions of life”

> “capable of being seen; perceptible by the eye, whether directly or with the aid of an instrument”

> “(of an act or course of conduct) contrary to morality or to accepted standards; deserving of blame or censure”

They are concise, grammatically controlled, and use the material after the semicolon as a genuine equivalent or refinement rather than as a mini-essay. Entry 2 is similarly credible:

> “to enter upon the first part of an action or process; (of an event or state) to come into being or into operation”

Its two clauses correspond cleanly to distinct senses.

### (d) Discriminability

Yes—at the set level, a fluent reader could probably distinguish these from an unselected sample of published dictionary entries with roughly **80–90% accuracy on structure alone**. For isolated individual entries, I would lower that to around **60–70%**, because entries 2, 4, 10, and 12 are structurally quite plausible.

The dominant cue would be the repeated **one-semicolon, two-stage architecture**:

> core gloss **;** appended synonym, qualification, contrast, or supplementary fact

The reader would also notice that the second half is unusually often introduced by frames such as:

> “it may…”

> “commonly…”

> “correspondingly…”

> “also…”

> “it differs…”

> “distinguished from…”

A published dictionary certainly uses all these devices, but not with this regularity across unrelated headwords. The giveaway is less any single malformed sentence than the conspicuous lack of editorial variation across the twelve.
